    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2168492">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2168492">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2168492)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2168492">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1361261"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1417253620 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">29 Nov 2014 09:33</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2168492">
									

<blockquote>
<p><em>Why now, then?</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>That really should have been the starting point of a story, rather than the ending point. As it stands, the researcher drinking himself into a maudlin stupor doesn't really strike me as a particularly good vantage point for something as ambitious as the concept of the Foundation decommissioning the entire planet.</p>
<p>There just seem to have been several avenues for a really interesting story here. Why is it that Earth is a local hotbed of anomalous activity? What place does the Foundation really have in this future society where it can exercise such overt power? Why, indeed, now? Instead of getting into any of these avenues, the tale cuts out right as it begins to be interesting.</p>

							</div>

								
					
						<div class="options">
				
