					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/thedeadlymoose" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(732274); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=732274&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164745" alt="thedeadlymoose" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=732274)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/thedeadlymoose" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(732274); return false;" >thedeadlymoose</a></span> <span class="odate time_1418017176 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 Dec 2014 05:39</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2174507">
									

<p>The central idea is very cool and you have remarkably good characterization. Enough to swing an upvote.</p>
<p>However, the piece does go astray with the wall of text central paragraph. It feels almost obligatory, like you were bored with your story's central concept before your story even got going. Like you were waaaaaay more interested in Reichardt. :P</p>
<p>Which is fine, but that doesn't mean you should half-ass a concept like &quot;Earth is an SCP that's being decommissioned&quot;. (Even if it's something simplistic &amp; straightforward, you can still play that for thematic weight.)</p>

							</div>

								
					
